auge-news-cyclingtips-3-1080x608.jpg 1080w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-DAG-3-derailleur-hanger-gauge-news-cyclingtips-3-16x9.jpg 16w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-DAG-3-derailleur-hanger-gauge-news-cyclingtips-3.jpg 1920w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1340px) 100vw, 1340px\" /><figcaption class=\"blocks-gallery-item__caption\">Park Tool has seemingly increased the fit tolerances of the rotating head.</figcaption></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1340\" height=\"754\" src=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-DAG-3-derailleur-hanger-gauge-news-cyclingtips-4-1340x754.jpg\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"488787\" data-full-url=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-DAG-3-derailleur-hanger-gauge-news-cyclingtips-4.jpg\" data-link=\"https://cyclingtips.com/?attachment_id=488787\" class=\"wp-image-488787\" srcset=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-DAG-3-derailleur-hanger-gauge-news-cyclingtips-4-1340x754.jpg 1340w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-DAG-3-derailleur-hanger-gauge-news-cyclingtips-4-650x366.jpg 650w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-DAG-3-derailleur-hanger-gauge-news-cyclingtips-4-190x107.jpg 190w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-DAG-3-derailleur-hanger-gauge-news-cyclingtips-4-1080x608.jpg 1080w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-DAG-3-derailleur-hanger-gauge-news-cyclingtips-4-16x9.jpg 16w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-DAG-3-derailleur-hanger-gauge-news-cyclingtips-4.jpg 1920w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1340px) 100vw, 1340px\" /><figcaption class=\"blocks-gallery-item__caption\">The aluminium tool body is keyed so the sliding indicator cannot turn off plane. </figcaption></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1340\" height=\"754\" src=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-DAG-3-derailleur-hanger-gauge-news-cyclingtips-1-1340x754.jpg\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"488782\" data-full-url=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-DAG-3-derailleur-hanger-gauge-news-cyclingtips-1.jpg\" data-link=\"https://cyclingtips.com/?attachment_id=488782\" class=\"wp-image-488782\" srcset=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-DAG-3-derailleur-hanger-gauge-news-cyclingtips-1-1340x754.jpg 1340w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-DAG-3-derailleur-hanger-gauge-news-cyclingtips-1-650x366.jpg 650w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-DAG-3-derailleur-hanger-gauge-news-cyclingtips-1-190x107.jpg 190w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-DAG-3-derailleur-hanger-gauge-news-cyclingtips-1-1080x608.jpg 1080w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-DAG-3-derailleur-hanger-gauge-news-cyclingtips-1-16x9.jpg 16w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-DAG-3-derailleur-hanger-gauge-news-cyclingtips-1.jpg 1920w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1340px) 100vw, 1340px\" /><figcaption class=\"blocks-gallery-item__caption\">The DAG-3 versus the DAG-2.2. </figcaption></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1340\" height=\"754\" src=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-DAG-3-derailleur-hanger-gauge-news-cyclingtips-2-1340x754.jpg\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"488784\" data-full-url=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-DAG-3-derailleur-hanger-gauge-news-cyclingtips-2.jpg\" data-link=\"https://cyclingtips.com/?attachment_id=488784\" class=\"wp-image-488784\" srcset=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-DAG-3-derailleur-hanger-gauge-news-cyclingtips-2-1340x754.jpg 1340w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-DAG-3-derailleur-hanger-gauge-news-cyclingtips-2-650x366.jpg 650w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-DAG-3-derailleur-hanger-gauge-news-cyclingtips-2-190x107.jpg 190w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-DAG-3-derailleur-hanger-gauge-news-cyclingtips-2-1080x608.jpg 1080w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-DAG-3-derailleur-hanger-gauge-news-cyclingtips-2-16x9.jpg 16w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-DAG-3-derailleur-hanger-gauge-news-cyclingtips-2.jpg 1920w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1340px) 100vw, 1340px\" /><figcaption class=\"blocks-gallery-item__caption\">A close-up of the DAG-3 against the DAG-2.2.</figcaption></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1340\" height=\"754\" src=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-DAG-3-derailleur-hanger-gauge-news-cyclingtips-6-1340x754.jpg\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"488790\" data-full-url=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-DAG-3-derailleur-hanger-gauge-news-cyclingtips-6.jpg\" data-link=\"https://cyclingtips.com/?attachment_id=488790\" class=\"wp-image-488790\" srcset=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-DAG-3-derailleur-hanger-gauge-news-cyclingtips-6-1340x754.jpg 1340w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-DAG-3-derailleur-hanger-gauge-news-cyclingtips-6-650x366.jpg 650w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-DAG-3-derailleur-hanger-gauge-news-cyclingtips-6-190x107.jpg 190w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-DAG-3-derailleur-hanger-gauge-news-cyclingtips-6-1080x608.jpg 1080w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-DAG-3-derailleur-hanger-gauge-news-cyclingtips-6-16x9.jpg 16w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-DAG-3-derailleur-hanger-gauge-news-cyclingtips-6.jpg 1920w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1340px) 100vw, 1340px\" /><figcaption class=\"blocks-gallery-item__caption\">The new DAG-3 against the Abbey Bike Tools HAG. The two tools take quite a different design approach. </figcaption></figure></li></ul></figure>\n\n\n\n<h2>QTH-1: Quick Change Bit Driver Set&nbsp;</h2>\n\n\n\n<p><a href=\"https://cyclingtips.com/2018/10/the-best-bit-based-cycling-multi-tool-shootout-16-tested/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Bit-based tools</a> are a great space-conscious way to cover a wide range of tool sizes, and the new QTH-1 is a workshop-grade offering with a unique feature. This T-handled bit driver (non-ratcheting) works with standard 1/4&#8243; bits and features a magnetic quick-change lever for easy one-handed changing of bits.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>The tool includes a bit holder that can either be magnetically attached to the side of a steel workstand or permanently mounted to a flat surface. Park Tool includes eight commonly used bit sizes, and the holder has space for two more.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>I received a test sample just hours ago and early impressions are that changing the bits in this tool is indeed a one-handed operation. The bit-holder acts as a loading and unloading dock for the bits, while the small sprung handle is an effective solution to disengage the bits. The construction quality is high and the tool is comfortable in the hand. This tool, including the bit holder, retails for US$57.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-3 is-cropped wp-block-gallery__slider\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1340\" height=\"754\" src=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-QTH-1-Quick-Change-Bit-Driver-Set-news-cyclingtips-4-1340x754.jpg\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"488808\" data-full-url=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-QTH-1-Quick-Change-Bit-Driver-Set-news-cyclingtips-4.jpg\" data-link=\"https://cyclingtips.com/?attachment_id=488808\" class=\"wp-image-488808\" srcset=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-QTH-1-Quick-Change-Bit-Driver-Set-news-cyclingtips-4-1340x754.jpg 1340w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-QTH-1-Quick-Change-Bit-Driver-Set-news-cyclingtips-4-650x366.jpg 650w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-QTH-1-Quick-Change-Bit-Driver-Set-news-cyclingtips-4-190x107.jpg 190w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-QTH-1-Quick-Change-Bit-Driver-Set-news-cyclingtips-4-1080x608.jpg 1080w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-QTH-1-Quick-Change-Bit-Driver-Set-news-cyclingtips-4-16x9.jpg 16w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-QTH-1-Quick-Change-Bit-Driver-Set-news-cyclingtips-4.jpg 1920w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1340px) 100vw, 1340px\" /><figcaption class=\"blocks-gallery-item__caption\">Pulling this lever removes the magnetic hold of the bit.</figcaption></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1340\" height=\"754\" src=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-QTH-1-Quick-Change-Bit-Driver-Set-news-cyclingtips-3-1340x754.jpg\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"488805\" data-full-url=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-QTH-1-Quick-Change-Bit-Driver-Set-news-cyclingtips-3.jpg\" data-link=\"https://cyclingtips.com/?attachment_id=488805\" class=\"wp-image-488805\" srcset=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-QTH-1-Quick-Change-Bit-Driver-Set-news-cyclingtips-3-1340x754.jpg 1340w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-QTH-1-Quick-Change-Bit-Driver-Set-news-cyclingtips-3-650x366.jpg 650w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-QTH-1-Quick-Change-Bit-Driver-Set-news-cyclingtips-3-190x107.jpg 190w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-QTH-1-Quick-Change-Bit-Driver-Set-news-cyclingtips-3-1080x608.jpg 1080w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-QTH-1-Quick-Change-Bit-Driver-Set-news-cyclingtips-3-16x9.jpg 16w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-QTH-1-Quick-Change-Bit-Driver-Set-news-cyclingtips-3.jpg 1920w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1340px) 100vw, 1340px\" /><figcaption class=\"blocks-gallery-item__caption\">The tool is made in the USA and offers an industrial feel.</figcaption></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1340\" height=\"754\" src=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-QTH-1-Quick-Change-Bit-Driver-Set-news-cyclingtips-2-1340x754.jpg\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"488803\" data-full-url=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-QTH-1-Quick-Change-Bit-Driver-Set-news-cyclingtips-2.jpg\" data-link=\"https://cyclingtips.com/?attachment_id=488803\" class=\"wp-image-488803\" srcset=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-QTH-1-Quick-Change-Bit-Driver-Set-news-cyclingtips-2-1340x754.jpg 1340w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-QTH-1-Quick-Change-Bit-Driver-Set-news-cyclingtips-2-650x366.jpg 650w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-QTH-1-Quick-Change-Bit-Driver-Set-news-cyclingtips-2-190x107.jpg 190w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-QTH-1-Quick-Change-Bit-Driver-Set-news-cyclingtips-2-1080x608.jpg 1080w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-QTH-1-Quick-Change-Bit-Driver-Set-news-cyclingtips-2-16x9.jpg 16w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-QTH-1-Quick-Change-Bit-Driver-Set-news-cyclingtips-2.jpg 1920w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1340px) 100vw, 1340px\" /><figcaption class=\"blocks-gallery-item__caption\">The tool handle can be stored with the bits. </figcaption></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1340\" height=\"754\" src=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-QTH-1-Quick-Change-Bit-Driver-Set-news-cyclingtips-1-1340x754.jpg\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"488802\" data-full-url=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-QTH-1-Quick-Change-Bit-Driver-Set-news-cyclingtips-1.jpg\" data-link=\"https://cyclingtips.com/?attachment_id=488802\" class=\"wp-image-488802\" srcset=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-QTH-1-Quick-Change-Bit-Driver-Set-news-cyclingtips-1-1340x754.jpg 1340w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-QTH-1-Quick-Change-Bit-Driver-Set-news-cyclingtips-1-650x366.jpg 650w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-QTH-1-Quick-Change-Bit-Driver-Set-news-cyclingtips-1-190x107.jpg 190w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-QTH-1-Quick-Change-Bit-Driver-Set-news-cyclingtips-1-1080x608.jpg 1080w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-QTH-1-Quick-Change-Bit-Driver-Set-news-cyclingtips-1-16x9.jpg 16w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-QTH-1-Quick-Change-Bit-Driver-Set-news-cyclingtips-1.jpg 1920w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1340px) 100vw, 1340px\" /><figcaption class=\"blocks-gallery-item__caption\">The magnetic bit holder can be attached in many places, including the side of a workstand. </figcaption></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1340\" height=\"754\" src=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-QTH-1-Quick-Change-Bit-Driver-Set-news-cyclingtips-5-1340x754.jpg\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"488811\" data-full-url=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-QTH-1-Quick-Change-Bit-Driver-Set-news-cyclingtips-5.jpg\" data-link=\"https://cyclingtips.com/?attachment_id=488811\" class=\"wp-image-488811\" srcset=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-QTH-1-Quick-Change-Bit-Driver-Set-news-cyclingtips-5-1340x754.jpg 1340w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-QTH-1-Quick-Change-Bit-Driver-Set-news-cyclingtips-5-650x366.jpg 650w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-QTH-1-Quick-Change-Bit-Driver-Set-news-cyclingtips-5-190x107.jpg 190w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-QTH-1-Quick-Change-Bit-Driver-Set-news-cyclingtips-5-1080x608.jpg 1080w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-QTH-1-Quick-Change-Bit-Driver-Set-news-cyclingtips-5-16x9.jpg 16w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-QTH-1-Quick-Change-Bit-Driver-Set-news-cyclingtips-5.jpg 1920w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1340px) 100vw, 1340px\" /><figcaption class=\"blocks-gallery-item__caption\">Even the bit holder shows some careful thought. </figcaption></figure></li></ul></figure>\n\n\n\n<h2>HBH-3: An Extendable Handlebar Holder</h2>\n\n\n\n<p>Bleeding hydraulic disc brakes often calls for getting the brake up at a weird angle so that gravity can assist. As you point the front wheel to the sky you’ll often find that the bars no longer stay where you want them, and this is where Park Tool’s new extendable handlebar holder comes in.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1340\" height=\"754\" src=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-HBH-3-Handlebar-holder-1340x754.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-488709\" srcset=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-HBH-3-Handlebar-holder-1340x754.jpg 1340w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-HBH-3-Handlebar-holder-650x366.jpg 650w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-HBH-3-Handlebar-holder-190x107.jpg 190w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-HBH-3-Handlebar-holder-1080x608.jpg 1080w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-HBH-3-Handlebar-holder-16x9.jpg 16w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-HBH-3-Handlebar-holder.jpg 1920w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1340px) 100vw, 1340px\" /><figcaption>The HBH-3 serves a simple function.</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>This telescoping tool simply allows you to affix the handlebars in a set position. The tool features rubber straps on articulating clamps that install onto any round tube from 12 to 60 mm in diameter, as well as working with a number of irregular and aero-shaped profiles. It can also be strapped around the arm or strut of a workstand. The tool extends from 45 to 81 cm in length, and collapses to 43 cm for storage. The HBH-3 is priced at US$43.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>This is the first time Park Tool has offered such a tool, but alternative options have existed for some time. Feedback Sports offers its Flop Stop for US$25, while a number of generic home mechanic bike stands include a similar thing. Park Tool’s version aims to work with a wider variety of tube shapes, offer a softer hold, all while being more sturdy.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Diamond Abrasive Adaptor for Carbon Fiber disc mount facing&nbsp;</h2>\n\n\n\n<p>Here’s a tool that shouldn’t need to exist. Designed to be used with Park Tool’s DT-5 or DT-5.2 <a href=\"https://cyclingtips.com/2018/05/complete-faq-to-road-disc-brakes/#troubleshooting\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">disc tab facing tools</a>, this is a diamond abrasive adapter for bringing wonky and poorly made carbon fibre brake tabs into a perpendicular plane.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1340\" height=\"754\" src=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-Diamond-Abrasive-Adaptor-for-Carbon-Fiber-disc-mount-facing-2197-news-cyclingtips-1-1340x754.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-488797\" srcset=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-Diamond-Abrasive-Adaptor-for-Carbon-Fiber-disc-mount-facing-2197-news-cyclingtips-1-1340x754.jpg 1340w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-Diamond-Abrasive-Adaptor-for-Carbon-Fiber-disc-mount-facing-2197-news-cyclingtips-1-650x366.jpg 650w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-Diamond-Abrasive-Adaptor-for-Carbon-Fiber-disc-mount-facing-2197-news-cyclingtips-1-190x107.jpg 190w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-Diamond-Abrasive-Adaptor-for-Carbon-Fiber-disc-mount-facing-2197-news-cyclingtips-1-1080x608.jpg 1080w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-Diamond-Abrasive-Adaptor-for-Carbon-Fiber-disc-mount-facing-2197-news-cyclingtips-1-16x9.jpg 16w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Park-Tool-Diamond-Abrasive-Adaptor-for-Carbon-Fiber-disc-mount-facing-2197-news-cyclingtips-1.jpg 1920w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1340px) 100vw, 1340px\" /><figcaption>On the left is the original cutter, on the right is the new diamond abrasive number. </figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Park Tool’s disc tab facing tools come with a cutter intended for use on metal, and using it on carbon fibre tends to leave disappointing results and a blunt tool. The new diamond abrasive adapter (#2197) should allow for easier and more accurate fixing of problematic carbon fibre frames and forks. This is a shop tool and so Park has not set a retail price.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Assorted bearing tools&nbsp;</h2>\n\n\n\n<p>While the four tools covered above are all new as of today, Park Tool also recently expanded its line of workshop bottom bracket and bearing service tools.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>The <a href=\"https://www.parktool.com/product/bottom-bracket-bearing-press-puller-set-bbp-2?category=New%20Products\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">BBP-2</a> is Park Tool’s answer to working with press-fit bottom brackets without the use of a hammer. The tool uses expanding collets and cups – along with the bearing press – to pull bearings and cups out. The press is then used to install new bearings and cups into place. Park also offers just the extractor set (<a href=\"https://www.parktool.com/product/bottom-bracket-bearing-extractor-add-on-set-bbp-aos?category=New%20Products\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">BBP-AOS</a>) as an add-on for those that own a press.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Park Tool also introduced its first <a href=\"https://www.parktool.com/product/slide-hammer-extractor-shx-1?category=New%20Products\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">slide hammer bearing extractor</a>, a workshop tool that allows the removal of cartridge bearings that have no easy access from behind. The set of five expanding collets work with bearings ranging from 6 to 32 mm internal diameter.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Lastly, there’s the Suspension Bearing Kit (<a href=\"https://www.parktool.com/product/suspension-bearing-kit-sbk-1?category=New%20Products\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">SBK-1</a>) which aims to be a versatile bearing press and puller kit for full suspension pivot servicing.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-3 is-cropped wp-block-gallery__slider\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1340\" height=\"754\" src=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/BBP-2-1340x754.jpg\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"488830\" data-full-url=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/BBP-2.jpg\" data-link=\"https://cyclingtips.com/?attachment_id=488830\" class=\"wp-image-488830\" srcset=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/BBP-2-1340x754.jpg 1340w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/BBP-2-650x366.jpg 650w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/BBP-2-190x107.jpg 190w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/BBP-2-1080x608.jpg 1080w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/BBP-2-16x9.jpg 16w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/BBP-2.jpg 1920w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1340px) 100vw, 1340px\" /><figcaption class=\"blocks-gallery-item__caption\">The BBP-2 aims to be a complete solution to (almost) all press-fit bottom brackets. </figcaption></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1340\" height=\"754\" src=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/park-tool-bbp-aos-1340x754.jpg\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"488833\" data-full-url=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/park-tool-bbp-aos.jpg\" data-link=\"https://cyclingtips.com/?attachment_id=488833\" class=\"wp-image-488833\" srcset=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/park-tool-bbp-aos-1340x754.jpg 1340w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/park-tool-bbp-aos-650x366.jpg 650w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/park-tool-bbp-aos-190x107.jpg 190w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/park-tool-bbp-aos-1080x608.jpg 1080w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/park-tool-bbp-aos-16x9.jpg 16w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/park-tool-bbp-aos.jpg 1920w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1340px) 100vw, 1340px\" /><figcaption class=\"blocks-gallery-item__caption\">The BBP-AOS covers just the removal portion of press-fit bottom brackets and can be an add-on for those that already have the press.</figcaption></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1340\" height=\"754\" src=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/park-tool-sbk-1-1340x754.jpg\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"488836\" data-full-url=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/park-tool-sbk-1.jpg\" data-link=\"https://cyclingtips.com/?attachment_id=488836\" class=\"wp-image-488836\" srcset=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/park-tool-sbk-1-1340x754.jpg 1340w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/park-tool-sbk-1-650x366.jpg 650w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/park-tool-sbk-1-190x107.jpg 190w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/park-tool-sbk-1-1080x608.jpg 1080w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/park-tool-sbk-1-16x9.jpg 16w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/park-tool-sbk-1.jpg 1920w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1340px) 100vw, 1340px\" /><figcaption class=\"blocks-gallery-item__caption\">The SBK-1 is for installing and removing cartridge bearings in full-suspension frames. </figcaption></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1340\" height=\"754\" src=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/park-tool-shx-1-1340x754.jpg\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"488839\" data-full-url=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/park-tool-shx-1.jpg\" data-link=\"https://cyclingtips.com/?attachment_id=488839\" class=\"wp-image-488839\" srcset=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/park-tool-shx-1-1340x754.jpg 1340w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/park-tool-shx-1-650x366.jpg 650w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/park-tool-shx-1-190x107.jpg 190w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/park-tool-shx-1-1080x608.jpg 1080w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/park-tool-shx-1-16x9.jpg 16w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/park-tool-shx-1.jpg 1920w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1340px) 100vw, 1340px\" /><figcaption class=\"blocks-gallery-item__caption\">The SHX-1 is Park Tool&#8217;s first slide hammer for blind hold bearing removal. </figcaption></figure></li></ul></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>For more information about any of the above, head to <a href=\"https://www.parktool.com/category/new\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">parktool.com</a>. </p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://cyclingtips.com/2021/03/park-tool-releases-dag-3-derailleur-hanger-gauge-qth-1-bit-tool-and-more/\">Park Tool releases new derailleur hanger gauge, bit tool and more</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://cyclingtips.com\">CyclingTips</a>.</p>","author":"Dave Rome","siteTitle":"CyclingTips","siteHash":"30feca30fb3902119bf2da6559e7337232527b61c9abe0a00f5d7543c6aa6c84","entryHash":"4cb42c5b15a08d478f40f89db21de96ab12c73a40772fc23bc3b49d3ca69cec5","category":"Cycling"}